{"articles_and_essays": null, "calendar_url": "https://www.loc.gov/item/sn95047324/?st=calendar", "cite_this": {"apa": "(1920, December 30)  <cite>The Punta Gorda herald</cite>. Retrieved from the Library of Congress, https://www.loc.gov/item/sn95047324/1920-12-30/ed-1/.", "chicago": "<cite>The Punta Gorda herald</cite>. (Punta Gorda, FL), Dec. 30 1920. https://www.loc.gov/item/sn95047324/1920-12-30/ed-1/.", "mla": "<cite>The Punta Gorda herald</cite>. (Punta Gorda, FL) 30 Dec. 1920, p. 4. Retrieved from the Library of Congress, www.loc.gov/item/sn95047324/1920-12-30/ed-1/."}, "fulltext_service": "https://tile.loc.gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service?segment=/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_dauer_ver03/data/sn95047324/00295865532/1920123001/0458.xml&format=alto_xml&full_text=1", "item": {"_version_": 1855514347662475264, "access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://www.loc.gov/item/sn95047324/1920-12-30/ed-1/", "http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn95047324/1920-12-30/ed-1/"], "batch": ["fu_dauer_ver03"], "call_number": ["Newspaper"], "campaigns": [], "composite_location": ["0/united states/", "1/united states/florida/", "2/united states/florida/charlotte/", "3/united states/florida/charlotte/punta gorda/"], "contributor_names": ["University of Florida"], "contributors": [{"university of florida": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=contributor:university+of+florida&fo=json"}], "created_published": ["Punta Gorda, Fla., December 30, 1920"], "date": "1920-12-30", "date_issued": "1920-12-30", "dates": [{"1920-12-30": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?dates=1920-12-30/1920-12-30&fo=json"}], "dates_of_publication": "1893-1958", "description": ["Punta Gorda, Fla."], "digital_id": ["https://www.loc.gov/chroniclingamerica/lccn/sn95047324/issues", "http://ufdc.ufl.edu/UF00075912"], "digitized": true, "digitized_label": "Present", "display_offsite": true, "extract_timestamp": "2026-01-27T16:59:17.713Z", "extract_urls": ["file:/service/ndnp//fu/batch_fu_dauer_ver03/data/sn95047324/00295865532/1920123001/1920123001_1.xml#ndnp/fu"], "format": [{"newspaper": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=original_format:newspaper&fo=json"}], "genre": ["Newspapers"], "group": ["ndnp/fu", "university-of-florida-awardee"], "hassegments": true, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/sn95047324/1920-12-30/ed-1/", "image_url": ["https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:fu:batch_fu_dauer_ver03:data:sn95047324:00295865532:1920123001:0455/full/pct:6.25/0/default.jpg#h=427&w=281", "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:fu:batch_fu_dauer_ver03:data:sn95047324:00295865532:1920123001:0455/full/pct:12.5/0/default.jpg#h=854&w=563"], "index": 4, "item": {"batch": ["fu_dauer_ver03"], "call_number": ["Newspaper"], "contributor_names": ["University of Florida"], "created_published": ["Punta Gorda, Fla., December 30, 1920"], "date": "1893", "date_issued": "1920-12-30", "dates": ["1920-12-30"], "digital_id": ["https://www.loc.gov/chroniclingamerica/lccn/sn95047324/issues", "http://ufdc.ufl.edu/UF00075912"], "digitized_label": "Present", "format": ["newspaper"], "genre": ["Newspapers"], "language": ["eng"], "library_of_congress_control_number": "sn95047324", "location": ["Punta Gorda (Fla.)", "Charlotte County (Fla.)", "Florida--Charlotte County", "Florida--Punta Gorda"], "medium": "10 pages", "newspaper_title": ["The Punta Gorda herald"], "notes": ["Weekly", "Began on Feb. 17, 1893.", "-v. 66, no. 48 (Dec. 4, 1958).", "Paul K. Garrett, editor.", "Archived issues are available in digital format as part of the Library of Congress Chronicling America online collection.", "Description based on: Vol. 10, no. 1 (Jan. 10, 1902).", "Herald (Punta Gorda, Fla.) (DLC)sn 95047325 (OCoLC)33600609"], "other_formats": ["https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/ndnp//fu/batch_fu_dauer_ver03/data/sn95047324/00295865532/1920123001/1920123001_1.xml", "http://lccn.loc.gov/sn95047324/marcxml"], "other_title": ["Herald"], "place_of_publication": "Punta Gorda, Fla.", "raw_lccn": "sn 95047324 ", "reel_numbers": ["00295865532"], "source_group": "ndnp/fu", "subjects": ["Punta Gorda (Fla.)--Newspapers", "Charlotte County (Fla.)--Newspapers", "Florida--Charlotte County", "Florida--Punta Gorda", "United States--Florida--Charlotte--Punta Gorda"], "summary": ["The Punta Gorda (FL) Herald [LCCN: sn95047324] covered such lively events as rum running, other smuggling activities, and lawlessness in general. Among news items of note is a visit by Carry Nation (1846-1911), a self-described \"bulldog\" activist for Prohibition. Nation came to Punta Gorda to counter the influence of a favorite son, General Albert W. Gilchrist. General Gilchrist, for whom Gilchrist County, Florida is named, favored the availability of alcohol. Her visit in 1908 had been orchestrated by Neva Chase Child, publisher of the Champion [LCCN sn95047227] in nearby Arcadia, Florida. In its June 18, 1908 issue, the Punta Gorda Herald reported that \"Only one paper in the entire state made any derogatory charge or insinuation against the private character of General Gilchrist and that paper is edited by a woman. We once heard an imminent Kentucky preacher say that a woman cannot tell the truth, and yet he had never read this paper that slandered Gilchrist and we, therefore, cannot imagine why he made the allegation.\" This rhetoric was thick with dry humor as the Punta Gorda Herald generally favored the General. Gilchrist, a hero of the Spanish-American war, was elected to the office of Governor of the State of Florida in November 1908, taking office in 1909. The Punta Gorda Herald was founded by Robert Kirby Seward in 1893 and published weekly during its early history. The Punta Gorda Herald literally watched the city of Punta Gorda grow up, starting with the arrival of the Florida Southern Railway. At that time Punta Gorda, now in Charlotte County (FL) was still part of DeSoto County (FL). Punta Gorda was first settled in 1882 and incorporated in 1900. Seward's press was foot-operated and produced two pages that were smaller than today's newspapers. Under the masthead was the slogan, \"In God We Trust, All Others Cash.\" One paper cost five cents while an annual subscription was a dollar. The \"inevitable\" fire, they were so common in Florida journalism history, in November of 1895 destroyed the print shop. The printing press was too large and cumbersome to move, so Seward was left with only a few cases of type and a small cabinet. After much encouragement and the financial backing of his brother-in-law, James Sandlin, and other businessmen, Seward rebuilt on the same site. He bought new equipment and boasted later that he never again missed publication. Seward sold the newspaper to Adrian Pettus Jordan in 1901. Prior to buying the Punta Gorda Herald, Jordan was known for his attacks on a railroad company that was acquiring land grants dishonestly. Then editor of the Wild Wood (FL) Orange Leaf [LCCN: sn97027627] in Sumter County (FL), Jordan's crusade brought about the state legislature's intervention into the affair. Jordan was also instrumental in getting General Gilchrist elected as State Representative and later Governor of Florida. There was even a failed assassination attempt on Jordan's life. He died in 1928 but his son, Adrian Crenshaw Jordan, assumed ownership, which he maintained until 1951. In 1958, the title changed to the simpler form, the Herald [LCCN: sn95047325]. Today (ca. 2008), it appears that the Herald has been succeeded by the Charlotte (FL) Sun-Herald [LCCN sn 91002725]. The Charlotte Sun-Herald website (ca. 2008) indicates that the Punta Gorda Herald has been published inside the Charlotte Sun-Herald on Wednesdays since 1991 when both papers were acquired by the Sun Coast Media Group, an independent Florida newspaper group. --E. Kesse, University of Florida Digital Library Center."], "title": "The Punta Gorda herald (Punta Gorda, Fla.), December 30, 1920"}, "language": ["english"], "languages": [{"english": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=language:english&fo=json"}], "library_of_congress_control_number": "sn95047324", "location": ["charlotte county", "florida", "united states", "charlotte", "punta gorda"], "location_city": ["punta gorda"], "location_country": ["united states"], "location_county": ["charlotte"], "location_state": ["florida"], "locations": [{"charlotte": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=location:charlotte&fo=json"}, {"charlotte county": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=location:charlotte+county&fo=json"}, {"florida": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=location:florida&fo=json"}, {"punta gorda": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=location:punta+gorda&fo=json"}, {"united states": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=location:united+states&fo=json"}], "locations_city": [{"punta gorda": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=location_city:punta+gorda&fo=json"}], "locations_country": [{"united states": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=location_country:united+states&fo=json"}], "locations_county": [{"charlotte": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=location_county:charlotte&fo=json"}], "locations_state": [{"florida": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=location_state:florida&fo=json"}], "medium": "10 pages", "method": "mets_filesec", "mime_type": ["image/jp2", "application/pdf", "text/xml", "image/jpeg"], "newspaper_title": ["The Punta Gorda herald"], "notes": ["Weekly", "Began on Feb. 17, 1893.", "-v. 66, no. 48 (Dec. 4, 1958).", "Paul K. Garrett, editor.", "Archived issues are available in digital format as part of the Library of Congress Chronicling America online collection.", "Description based on: Vol. 10, no. 1 (Jan. 10, 1902).", "Herald (Punta Gorda, Fla.) (DLC)sn 95047325 (OCoLC)33600609"], "number": ["00295865532", "sn95047324", "1"], "number_edition": ["1"], "number_lccn": ["sn95047324"], "number_reel": ["00295865532"], "numeric_shelf_id": 192012301, "online_format": ["image", "pdf", "online text"], "original_format": ["newspaper"], "other_formats": [{"label": "MODSXML Record", "link": "//tile.loc.gov/storage-services/service/ndnp//fu/batch_fu_dauer_ver03/data/sn95047324/00295865532/1920123001/1920123001_1.xml"}, {"label": "MARCXML Record", "link": "//lccn.loc.gov/sn95047324/marcxml"}], "other_title": ["Herald"], "partof": [{"count": 527, "title": "the punta gorda herald (punta gorda, fla.) 1893-1958", "url": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=partof:the+punta+gorda+herald+%28punta+gorda,+fla.%29+1893-1958&fo=json"}, {"count": 3203926, "title": "chronicling america", "url": "https://www.loc.gov/collections/chronicling-america/?fo=json"}, {"count": 3225157, "title": "serial and government publications division", "url": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=partof:serial+and+government+publications+division&fo=json"}], "partof_collection": ["chronicling america"], "partof_division": ["serial and government publications division"], "partof_title": ["the punta gorda herald (punta gorda, fla.) 1893-1958"], "place_of_publication": "Punta Gorda, Fla.", "publication_frequency": ["weekly"], "raw_lccn": "sn 95047324 ", "reel_numbers": ["00295865532"], "resources": [{"files": 10, "image": "https://tile.loc.gov/image-services/iiif/service:ndnp:fu:batch_fu_dauer_ver03:data:sn95047324:00295865532:1920123001:0455/full/pct:6.25/0/default.jpg", "url": "https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn95047324/1920-12-30/ed-1/", "word_coordinates": "https://tile.loc.gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service"}], "rights": ["<p>The Library of Congress believes that the newspapers in Chronicling America are in the public domain or have no known copyright restrictions.  Newspapers published in the United States more than 95 years ago are in the public domain in their entirety. Any newspapers in Chronicling America that were published less than 95 years ago are also believed to be in the public domain, but may contain some copyrighted third party materials. Researchers using newspapers published less than 95 years ago should be alert for modern content (for example, registered and renewed for copyright and published with notice) that may be copyrighted.  Responsibility for making an independent legal assessment of an item and securing any necessary permissions ultimately rests with persons desiring to use the item.</p>\n<p>The NEH awardee responsible for producing each digital object is presented in the Chronicling America page display, below the page image  \u2013 e.g. Image produced by the Library of Congress. For more information on current NDNP awardees, see <a href=\"https://www.loc.gov/ndnp/listawardees.html\">https://www.loc.gov/ndnp/listawardees.html</a>.</p>\n<p>For more information on Library of Congress policies and disclaimers regarding rights and reproductions, see <a href=\"https://www.loc.gov/homepage/legal.html\">https://www.loc.gov/homepage/legal.html</a></p>"], "score": 14.45633, "shard": "04", "shelf_id": "sn95047324, 1920-12-30, Edition 1", "site": ["chroniclingamerica"], "source_group": "ndnp/fu", "source_modified": "2000-01-01T12:00:00Z", "subject": ["newspapers", "charlotte county", "florida", "united states", "punta gorda (fla.)", "charlotte", "punta gorda", "charlotte county (fla.)"], "subject_headings": ["Punta Gorda (Fla.)--Newspapers", "Charlotte County (Fla.)--Newspapers", "Florida--Charlotte County", "Florida--Punta Gorda", "United States--Florida--Charlotte--Punta Gorda"], "subjects": [{"charlotte": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=subject:charlotte&fo=json"}, {"charlotte county": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=subject:charlotte+county&fo=json"}, {"charlotte county (fla.)": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=subject:charlotte+county+%28fla.%29&fo=json"}, {"florida": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=subject:florida&fo=json"}, {"newspapers": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=subject:newspapers&fo=json"}, {"punta gorda": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=subject:punta+gorda&fo=json"}, {"punta gorda (fla.)": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=subject:punta+gorda+%28fla.%29&fo=json"}, {"united states": "https://www.loc.gov/search/?fa=subject:united+states&fo=json"}], "summary": ["The Punta Gorda (FL) Herald [LCCN: sn95047324] covered such lively events as rum running, other smuggling activities, and lawlessness in general. Among news items of note is a visit by Carry Nation (1846-1911), a self-described \"bulldog\" activist for Prohibition. Nation came to Punta Gorda to counter the influence of a favorite son, General Albert W. Gilchrist. General Gilchrist, for whom Gilchrist County, Florida is named, favored the availability of alcohol. Her visit in 1908 had been orchestrated by Neva Chase Child, publisher of the Champion [LCCN sn95047227] in nearby Arcadia, Florida. In its June 18, 1908 issue, the Punta Gorda Herald reported that \"Only one paper in the entire state made any derogatory charge or insinuation against the private character of General Gilchrist and that paper is edited by a woman. We once heard an imminent Kentucky preacher say that a woman cannot tell the truth, and yet he had never read this paper that slandered Gilchrist and we, therefore, cannot imagine why he made the allegation.\" This rhetoric was thick with dry humor as the Punta Gorda Herald generally favored the General. Gilchrist, a hero of the Spanish-American war, was elected to the office of Governor of the State of Florida in November 1908, taking office in 1909. The Punta Gorda Herald was founded by Robert Kirby Seward in 1893 and published weekly during its early history. The Punta Gorda Herald literally watched the city of Punta Gorda grow up, starting with the arrival of the Florida Southern Railway. At that time Punta Gorda, now in Charlotte County (FL) was still part of DeSoto County (FL). Punta Gorda was first settled in 1882 and incorporated in 1900. Seward's press was foot-operated and produced two pages that were smaller than today's newspapers. Under the masthead was the slogan, \"In God We Trust, All Others Cash.\" One paper cost five cents while an annual subscription was a dollar. The \"inevitable\" fire, they were so common in Florida journalism history, in November of 1895 destroyed the print shop. The printing press was too large and cumbersome to move, so Seward was left with only a few cases of type and a small cabinet. After much encouragement and the financial backing of his brother-in-law, James Sandlin, and other businessmen, Seward rebuilt on the same site. He bought new equipment and boasted later that he never again missed publication. Seward sold the newspaper to Adrian Pettus Jordan in 1901. Prior to buying the Punta Gorda Herald, Jordan was known for his attacks on a railroad company that was acquiring land grants dishonestly. Then editor of the Wild Wood (FL) Orange Leaf [LCCN: sn97027627] in Sumter County (FL), Jordan's crusade brought about the state legislature's intervention into the affair. Jordan was also instrumental in getting General Gilchrist elected as State Representative and later Governor of Florida. There was even a failed assassination attempt on Jordan's life. He died in 1928 but his son, Adrian Crenshaw Jordan, assumed ownership, which he maintained until 1951. In 1958, the title changed to the simpler form, the Herald [LCCN: sn95047325]. Today (ca. 2008), it appears that the Herald has been succeeded by the Charlotte (FL) Sun-Herald [LCCN sn 91002725]. The Charlotte Sun-Herald website (ca. 2008) indicates that the Punta Gorda Herald has been published inside the Charlotte Sun-Herald on Wednesdays since 1991 when both papers were acquired by the Sun Coast Media Group, an independent Florida newspaper group. --E. Kesse, University of Florida Digital Library Center."], "timestamp": "2026-01-27T23:26:07.801Z", "title": "The Punta Gorda herald (Punta Gorda, Fla.), December 30, 1920", "type": ["issue"], "url": "https://www.loc.gov/item/sn95047324/1920-12-30/ed-1/"}, "locations": null, "method": "mets_filesec", "more_like_this": [{"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://www.loc.gov/item/sn95047324/", "http://lccn.loc.gov/sn95047324", "https://search.catalog.loc.gov/instances/68e1574c-9093-5a37-bf8f-e7a5f2668330"], "batch": ["fu_dauer_ver03"], "campaigns": [], "date": "1893", "description": ["The Punta Gorda (FL) Herald [LCCN: sn95047324] covered such lively events as rum running, other smuggling activities, and lawlessness in general. Among news items of note is a visit by Carry Nation (1846-1911), a self-described \"bulldog\" activist for Prohibition. Nation came to Punta Gorda to counter the influence of a favorite son, General Albert W. Gilchrist. General Gilchrist, for whom Gilchrist County, Florida is named, favored the availability of alcohol. Her visit in 1908 had been orchestrated by Neva Chase Child, publisher of the Champion [LCCN sn95047227] in nearby Arcadia, Florida. In its June 18, 1908 issue, the Punta Gorda Herald reported that \"Only one paper in the entire state made any derogatory charge or insinuation against the private character of General Gilchrist and that paper is edited by a woman. We once heard an imminent Kentucky preacher say that a woman cannot tell the truth, and yet he had never read this paper that slandered Gilchrist and we, therefore, cannot imagine why he made the allegation.\" This rhetoric was thick with dry humor as the Punta Gorda Herald generally favored the General. Gilchrist, a hero of the Spanish-American war, was elected to the office of Governor of the State of Florida in November 1908, taking office in 1909. The Punta Gorda Herald was founded by Robert Kirby Seward in 1893 and published weekly during its early history. The Punta Gorda Herald literally watched the city of Punta Gorda grow up, starting with the arrival of the Florida Southern Railway. At that time Punta Gorda, now in Charlotte County (FL) was still part of DeSoto County (FL). Punta Gorda was first settled in 1882 and incorporated in 1900. Seward's press was foot-operated and produced two pages that were smaller than today's newspapers. Under the masthead was the slogan, \"In God We Trust, All Others Cash.\" One paper cost five cents while an annual subscription was a dollar. The \"inevitable\" fire, they were so common in Florida journalism history, in November of 1895 destroyed the print shop. The printing press was too large and cumbersome to move, so Seward was left with only a few cases of type and a small cabinet. After much encouragement and the financial backing of his brother-in-law, James Sandlin, and other businessmen, Seward rebuilt on the same site. He bought new equipment and boasted later that he never again missed publication. Seward sold the newspaper to Adrian Pettus Jordan in 1901. Prior to buying the Punta Gorda Herald, Jordan was known for his attacks on a railroad company that was acquiring land grants dishonestly. Then editor of the Wild Wood (FL) Orange Leaf [LCCN: sn97027627] in Sumter County (FL), Jordan's crusade brought about the state legislature's intervention into the affair. Jordan was also instrumental in getting General Gilchrist elected as State Representative and later Governor of Florida. There was even a failed assassination attempt on Jordan's life. He died in 1928 but his son, Adrian Crenshaw Jordan, assumed ownership, which he maintained until 1951. In 1958, the title changed to the simpler form, the Herald [LCCN: sn95047325]. Today (ca. 2008), it appears that the Herald has been succeeded by the Charlotte (FL) Sun-Herald [LCCN sn 91002725]. The Charlotte Sun-Herald website (ca. 2008) indicates that the Punta Gorda Herald has been published inside the Charlotte Sun-Herald on Wednesdays since 1991 when both papers were acquired by the Sun Coast Media Group, an independent Florida newspaper group. --E. Kesse, University of Florida Digital Library Center."], "digitized": true, "extract_timestamp": "2026-06-05T18:25:17.113Z", "group": ["newspaper-titles", "ndnp/newspapers", "catalog-split-03", "catalog", "united-states-newspaper-directory", "main-catalog-split-03"], "hassegments": false, "id": "http://www.loc.gov/item/sn9504732